issue.title: Moving cursor down misbehaves when font size > 1 and no space left
issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
When printing text using font size == 2 and then moving the cursor down via either a move-to-next-line or a move-to that jumps down 2 rows and sets the cursor at column 0, the cursor actually moves only 1 row down and ends up printing text on the same line as the previous one. This happens when there's not enough vertical space to show both lines (e.g. 3 rows in this example).

**To Reproduce**
To reproduce this behavior:

1. Create a rust project via `cargo new potato`
2. `cd potato`
3. edit `Cargo.toml` so under `[dependencies]` you have a `crossterm = "0.29"`
4. edit `src/main.rs` and paste the following:

```rust
use crossterm::{
    cursor,
    event::{self, Event, KeyCode},
    style,
    terminal::{self, disable_raw_mode, enable_raw_mode, ClearType},
    ExecutableCommand,
};
use std::io::{stdout, Write};

fn run() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let mut stdout = stdout();
    loop {
        stdout.execute(terminal::Clear(ClearType::All))?;
        stdout.execute(cursor::MoveTo(0, 0))?;

        // print one line of normal sized text, move down
        stdout.execute(style::Print("normal text"))?;
        stdout.execute(cursor::MoveToNextLine(1))?;

        // print a size 2 line and move down 2 lines
        stdout.execute(style::Print("\x1b]66;s=2;this is some text\x1b\\"))?;
        stdout.execute(cursor::MoveTo(0, 3))?;
        // instead of the `MoveTo` above you can do this; it behaves the same way
        //stdout.execute(cursor::MoveToNextLine(2))?;

        // now print another size 2 line
        stdout.execute(style::Print("\x1b]66;s=2;this is another text\x1b\\"))?;
        stdout.flush()?;
        // wait until we read `q' otherwise keep looping
        let event = event::read()?;
        if let Event::Key(key) = event {
            if key.code == KeyCode::Char('q') {
                break;
            }
        }
        continue;
    }
    Ok(())
}

fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    enable_raw_mode()?;
    let _ = run();
    disable_raw_mode()?;
    Ok(())
}
```

5. `cargo run` (press `q` to exit)
6. Shrink the terminal vertically until there's only 3 rows left.
7. Notice how the second line that contains font size 2 text shows up appended after the first one rather than at a new line.

The expectation here should be that I see half of the first font size 2 line and the entirety of the second one, but instead I see half of the first one and a mispositioned second line.

**Screenshots**

Screenshot

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/7f0fd955-1da2-49c3-8d05-e38177d92004)

And video:

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2f8d5183-8d27-4830-a45a-0990e7e22f27
